# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: hashicorp-nomad
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] HashiCorp is headquartered in San Francisco, but its employees are distributed across the United States, Canada, Australia, India, and Europe.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] HashiCorp offers source-available libraries and other proprietary products.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] HashiCorp was founded in 2012 by Mitchell Hashimoto and Armon Dadgar, two classmates from the University of Washington's Paul G.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] Allen School of Computer Science and Engineering .
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] Co-founder Hashimoto was previously working on open-source software called Vagrant, which became incorporated into HashiCorp.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] On 29 November 2021, HashiCorp set terms for its IPO at $68-$72 at a valuation of $13 billion.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] HashiCorp considers its workers to be remote workers first rather than coming into an office on a full-time basis.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] Around April 2021, a supply chain attack using code auditing tool codecov allowed hackers limited access to HashiCorp's customers networks.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] As a result, private credentials were leaked.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] HashiCorp revoked a private signing key and asked its customers to use a new rotated key.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] Mitchell Hashimoto resigned from the company in December 2023.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] On April 24, 2024, the company announced it had entered into an agreement to be acquired by IBM for $6.4 billion, with the transaction expected to close by the end of the same year.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] This led to the Competition and Markets Authority of the United Kingdom launching an investigation into the acquisition in late 2024.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] The deal closed on February 27, 2025 for $6.4 billion after receiving the necessary regulatory approvals.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] HashiCorp provides a suite of tools intended to support the development and deployment of large-scale service-oriented software installations.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] Each tool is aimed at specific stages in the life cycle of a software application, with a focus on automation.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] Many have a plugin-oriented architecture in order to provide integration with third-party technologies and services.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/hashicorp] Additional proprietary features for some of these tools are offered commercially and are aimed at enterprise customers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] A **job scheduler** is a computer application for controlling unattended background program execution of jobs.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] This is commonly called **batch scheduling**, as execution of non-interactive jobs is often called batch processing, though traditional *job* and *batch* are distinguished and contrasted; see that page for details.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Other synonyms include **batch system**, **distributed resource management system** (**DRMS**), **distributed resource manager** (**DRM**), and, commonly today, **workload automation** (**WLA**).
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] The data structure of jobs to run is known as the job queue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Modern job schedulers typically provide a graphical user interface and a single point of control for definition and monitoring of background executions in a distributed network of computers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Increasingly, job schedulers are required to orchestrate the integration of real-time business activities with traditional background IT processing across different operating system platforms and business application environments.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] If software from a completely different area includes all or some of those features, this software can be considered to have job scheduling capabilities.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Most operating systems, such as Unix and Windows, provide basic job scheduling capabilities, notably by at and batch, cron, and the Windows Task Scheduler.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Web hosting services provide job scheduling capabilities through a control panel or a webcron solution.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Many programs such as DBMS, backup, ERPs, and BPM also include relevant job-scheduling capabilities.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Operating system ("OS") or point program supplied job-scheduling will not usually provide the ability to schedule beyond a single OS instance or outside the remit of the specific program.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] These advanced capabilities can be written by in-house developers but are more often provided by suppliers who specialize in systems-management software.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] There are many concepts that are central to almost every job scheduler implementation and that are widely recognized with minimal variations: jobs, dependencies, job streams, and users.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Beyond the basic, single OS instance scheduling tools there are two major architectures that exist for Job Scheduling software.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Job schedulers have been one of the major components of IT infrastructure since the early mainframe systems.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] At first, stacks of punched cards were processed one after the other, hence the term "batch processing".
[src:hashicorp-nomad/job-scheduler] Various schemes are used to decide which particular job to run.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-concepts] Nomad is a highly available, distributed, data-center aware cluster and application scheduler designed to support the modern datacenter with support for long-running services, batch jobs, and much more.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-concepts] Learn how to use Nomad to schedule and orchestrate workloads.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-concepts] Become familiar with the core concepts of Nomad.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-concepts] Use Nomad Pack to deploy popular applications to Nomad.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-concepts] Automatically maintain your cluster and workload instance count to respond to demand while minimizing over-provisioning cost.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-concepts] Learn the features operators will need to build and maintain Nomad clusters.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] This guide is the best place to start with Nomad.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] We cover what Nomad is, what problems it can solve, how it compares to existing software, and how you can get started using it.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] If you are familiar with the basics of Nomad, the documentation and tutorials provide a more detailed reference of available features.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is a flexible workload orchestrator that enables an organization to easily deploy and manage any containerized or legacy application using a single, unified workflow.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad can run a diverse workload of Docker, non-containerized, microservice, and batch applications.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad enables developers to use declarative infrastructure-as-code for deploying applications.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad uses bin packing to efficiently schedule jobs and optimize for resource utilization.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is supported on macOS, Windows, and Linux.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is widely adopted and used in production by PagerDuty, Target, Citadel, Trivago, SAP, Pandora, Roblox, eBay, Deluxe Entertainment, and more.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] There are many relevant categories for comparison including cluster managers, resource managers, workload managers, and schedulers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] There are many existing tools in each category, and the comparisons are not exhaustive of the entire space.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Kubernetes and Nomad support similar core use cases for application deployment and management, but they differ in a few key ways.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Kubernetes aims to provide all the features needed to run Linux container-based applications including cluster management, scheduling, service discovery, monitoring, and secrets management.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad only aims to focus on cluster management and scheduling, and Nomad is designed with the Unix philosophy of having a small scope while composing with tools like Consul for service discovery/service mesh and Vault for secret management.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Kubernetes is designed as a collection of more than a half-dozen interoperating services which together provide the full functionality.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Coordination and storage is provided by etcd at the core.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] The state is wrapped by API controllers which are consumed by other services that provide higher level APIs for features like scheduling.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Kubernetes supports running in a highly available configuration but is operationally complex to setup.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is a single binary, both for clients and servers, and requires no external services for coordination or storage.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad combines a lightweight resource manager and a sophisticated scheduler into a single system.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] By default, Nomad is distributed, highly available, and operationally simple.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] While Kubernetes is specifically focused on Linux containers, Nomad is more general purpose.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad supports virtualized, containerized and standalone applications, including Docker, Java, IIS on Windows, Qemu, etc.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is designed with extensible drivers and support will be extended to all common drivers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] A full Kubernetes installation for a production environment is time consuming, operationally complex, and resource intensive.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] An increasing number of implementations are created by the Kubernetes community to mitigate these challenges, such as minikube, kubeadm, k3s, and more.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] These trimmed versions of Kubernetes offer easier adoption for development and testing, but lead to inconsistency in capabilities, configuration, and management when moving into production.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] In contrast to Kubernetes' fragmented distributions, Nomad as a single lightweight binary can be deployed in local dev, production, on-prem, at the edge, and in the cloud in a consistent manner, and provides the same operational ease-of-use across all environments.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Kubernetes documentation states that they support clusters up to 5,000 nodes and 300,000 total containers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] As the environment grows, the interoperating components with different constraints compound the operational complexity.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Even operators at Google revealed the significant challenges of managing the system at scale.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] The lack of maturity in the Federation project and the additional overhead of managing a centralized management plane also make it a hard experience to deploy a distributed system that spans multiple clusters.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad has been proven to scale to cluster sizes that exceed 10,000 nodes in real-world production environments.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] It can be deployed across multiple availability zones, regions, and data centers with a single cluster or multiple clusters.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is designed to natively handle multi-cluster deployments without the overhead of running clusters on clusters.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] This makes it easier to scale the application deployment across multiple datacenters, regions, and clouds with no additional complexity.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad has performed strenuous benchmark on scalability with 1 million container challenge in 2016 and 2 million container challenge in 2020.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] These tests are aimed to validate Nomad's architectural design and ensure that Nomad performs under the most extreme requirements.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Enterprises are comprised of multiple groups of people (business units) with different projects, infrastructure environments, technical competencies, team sizes, budgets, and SLAs.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Each group has different requirements and leverages technologies based on their particular needs and constraints.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Medium to large scale enterprises run into challenges when trying to standardize hundreds to thousands of software developers and administrators onto one single orchestrator (Kubernetes, Nomad, Mesos) as no scheduler today fits all applications, environments, projects, and teams.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Companies in the Global 2000 today such as Intel, Autodesk and GitHub with multiple products and business units organically run Nomad and Kubernetes to supplement each other.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] They leverage each scheduler to its strengths with Kubernetes for its cutting edge ecosystem and Nomad for simple maintenance and flexibility in core scheduling.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] We continue to see small enterprises continue to standardize on a single orchestrator given the natural staffing and organizational constraints.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] There are not enough DevOps members to maintain more than one orchestrator, not enough developers to warrant diverging workflows, or simply not enough workload diversity to require more than one orchestrator.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Amazon Web Services provides the Elastic Container Service (ECS), which is a cluster manager.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] The ECS service is only available within AWS and can only be used for Docker workloads.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Amazon provides customers with the agent that is installed on EC2 instances, but does not provide the servers which are a hosted service of AWS.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] There are a number of fundamental differences between Nomad and ECS.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is completely open source, including both the client and server components.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] By contrast, only the agent code for ECS is open and the servers are closed sourced and managed by Amazon.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] As a side effect of the ECS servers being managed by AWS, it is not possible to use ECS outside of AWS.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad is agnostic to the environment in which it is run, supporting public and private clouds, as well as bare metal datacenters.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Clusters in Nomad can span multiple datacenters and regions, meaning a single cluster could be managing machines on AWS, Azure, and GCE simultaneously.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] The ECS service is specifically focused on containers and the Docker engine, while Nomad is more general purpose.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad supports virtualized, containerized, and standalone applications, including Docker.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Terraform is a tool for building, changing, and versioning infrastructure safely and efficiently.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Configuration files describe to Terraform the components needed to run a single application or your entire datacenter.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Terraform generates an execution plan describing what it will do to reach the desired state, and then executes it to build the described infrastructure.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] As the configuration changes, Terraform is able to determine what changed and create incremental execution plans which can be applied.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad differs from Terraform in a number of key ways.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Terraform is designed to support any type of resource including low-level components such as compute instances, storage, and networking, as well as high-level components such as DNS entries, SaaS features, etc.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Terraform knows how to create, provision, and manage the lifecycle of these resources.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad runs on existing infrastructure and manages the lifecycle of applications running on that infrastructure.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Another major distinction is that Terraform is an offline tool that runs to completion, while Nomad is an online system with long lived servers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Nomad allows new jobs to be submitted, existing jobs updated or deleted, and can handle node failures.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] This requires operating continuously instead of in a single shot like Terraform.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] For small infrastructures with only a handful of servers or applications, the complexity of Nomad may not outweigh simply using Terraform to statically assign applications to machines.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] At larger scales, Terraform should be used to provision capacity for Nomad, and Nomad used to manage scheduling applications to machines dynamically.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/nomad-intro] Review use cases to understand the many ways Nomad is used in production today across many industries to solve critical, real-world business objectives.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] In system administration, **orchestration** is the automated configuration, coordination, deployment, and management of computer systems and software.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] Many tools exist for automating server configuration and management.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] Orchestration is often discussed in the context of service-oriented architecture, virtualization, provisioning, converged infrastructure, and dynamic data center topics.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] Orchestration in this sense is about aligning the business request with the applications, data, and infrastructure.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] In the context of cloud computing, the main difference between workflow automation and orchestration is that workflows are processed and completed as processes within a single domain for automation purposes.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] Orchestration, meanwhile, incorporates workflows and provides a directed action towards larger goals and objectives.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] In the context of application programming interfaces (APIs), API orchestration refers to the process of integrating multiple APIs into a unified system to streamline workflows and enhance user experience.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] The approach coordinates the flow of data, the execution sequence, and the dependencies among different APIs to achieve a defined business objective.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/orchestration-computing] API orchestration is commonly applied in environments that utilize microservices architectures or legacy systems, where the interaction of several APIs is required to complete a task.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In computing, **scheduling** is the action of assigning resources to perform tasks.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The resources may be processors, network links or expansion cards.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The tasks may be threads, processes or data flows.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The scheduling activity is carried out by a mechanism called a **scheduler**.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Schedulers are often designed so as to keep all computer resources busy (as in load balancing), allow multiple users to share system resources effectively, or to achieve a target quality-of-service.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Scheduling is fundamental to computation itself, and an intrinsic part of the execution model of a computer system; the concept of scheduling makes it possible to have computer multitasking with a single central processing unit (CPU).
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In practice, these goals often conflict (e.g. throughput versus latency), thus a scheduler will implement a suitable compromise.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Preference is measured by any one of the concerns mentioned above, depending upon the user's needs and objectives.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In real-time environments, such as embedded systems for automatic control in industry (for example robotics), the scheduler also must ensure that processes can meet deadlines; this is crucial for keeping the system stable.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Scheduled tasks can also be distributed to remote devices across a network and managed through an administrative back end.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The scheduler is an operating system module that selects the next jobs to be admitted into the system and the next process to run.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Operating systems may feature up to three distinct scheduler types: a *long-term scheduler* (also known as an admission scheduler or high-level scheduler), a *mid-term or medium-term scheduler*, and a *short-term scheduler*.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The names suggest the relative frequency with which their functions are performed.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The process scheduler is a part of the operating system that decides which process runs at a certain point in time.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] It usually has the ability to pause a running process, move it to the back of the running queue and start a new process; such a scheduler is known as a *preemptive scheduler*.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] If the scheduler cannot pause a running process and start a new process, the scheduler is a *cooperative scheduler*.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] We distinguish between *long-term scheduling*, *medium-term scheduling*, and *short-term scheduling* based on how often decisions must be made.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Thus, this scheduler dictates what processes are to run on a system, the degree of concurrency to be supported at any one time – whether many or few processes are to be executed concurrently, and how the split between I/O-intensive and CPU-intensive processes is to be handled.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The long-term scheduler is responsible for controlling the degree of multiprogramming.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In general, most processes can be described as either I/O-bound or CPU-bound.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] An I/O-bound process is one that spends more of its time doing I/O than it spends doing computations.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] A CPU-bound process, in contrast, generates I/O requests infrequently, using more of its time doing computations.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] It is important that a long-term scheduler selects a good process mix of I/O-bound and CPU-bound processes.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] If all processes are I/O-bound, the ready queue will almost always be empty, and the short-term scheduler will have little to do.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] On the other hand, if all processes are CPU-bound, the I/O waiting queue will almost always be empty, devices will go unused, and again the system will be unbalanced.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The system with the best performance will thus have a combination of CPU-bound and I/O-bound processes.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In modern operating systems, this is used to make sure that real-time processes get enough CPU time to finish their tasks.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Long-term scheduling is also important in large-scale systems such as batch processing systems, computer clusters, supercomputers, and render farms.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] For example, in concurrent systems, coscheduling of interacting processes is often required to prevent them from blocking due to waiting on each other.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In these cases, special-purpose job scheduler software is typically used to assist these functions, in addition to any underlying admission scheduling support in the operating system.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Some operating systems only allow new tasks to be added if it is sure all real-time deadlines can still be met.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The specific heuristic algorithm used by an operating system to accept or reject new tasks is the *admission control mechanism*.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The *medium-term scheduler* temporarily removes processes from main memory and places them in secondary memory (such as a hard disk drive) or vice versa, which is commonly referred to as *swapping out* or *swapping in* (also incorrectly as *paging out* or *paging in*).
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In many systems today (those that support mapping virtual address space to secondary storage other than the swap file), the medium-term scheduler may actually perform the role of the long-term scheduler, by treating binaries as *swapped-out processes* upon their execution.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In this way, when a segment of the binary is required, it can be swapped in on demand, or *lazy loaded*, also called demand paging.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The *short-term scheduler* (also known as the *CPU scheduler*) decides which of the ready, in-memory processes is to be executed (allocated a CPU) after a clock interrupt, an I/O interrupt, an operating system call or another form of signal.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Thus, the short-term scheduler makes scheduling decisions much more frequently than the long-term or mid-term schedulers – A scheduling decision will, at a minimum, have to be made after every time slice, and these are very short.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] This scheduler can be preemptive, implying that it is capable of forcibly removing processes from a CPU when it decides to allocate that CPU to another process, or non-preemptive (also known as *voluntary* or *co-operative*), in which case the scheduler is unable to *force* processes off the CPU.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Another component that is involved in the CPU-scheduling function is the dispatcher, which is the module that gives control of the CPU to the process selected by the short-term scheduler.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] It receives control in kernel mode as the result of an interrupt or system call.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The dispatcher should be as fast as possible since it is invoked during every process switch.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] During the context switches, the processor is virtually idle for a fraction of time, thus unnecessary context switches should be avoided.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The time it takes for the dispatcher to stop one process and start another is known as the *dispatch latency*.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] A **scheduling discipline** (also called **scheduling policy** or **scheduling algorithm**) is an algorithm used for distributing resources among parties that simultaneously and asynchronously request them.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Scheduling disciplines are used in routers (to handle packet traffic) as well as in operating systems (to share CPU time among both threads and processes), disk drives (I/O scheduling), printers (print spooler), most embedded systems, etc.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The main purposes of scheduling algorithms are to minimize resource starvation and to ensure fairness amongst the parties utilizing the resources.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Scheduling deals with the problem of deciding which of the outstanding requests is to be allocated resources.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] There are many different scheduling algorithms.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In this section, we introduce several of them.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In packet-switched computer networks and other statistical multiplexing, the notion of a **scheduling algorithm** is used as an alternative to first-come first-served queuing of data packets.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The simplest best-effort scheduling algorithms are round-robin, fair queuing (a max-min fair scheduling algorithm), proportional-fair scheduling and maximum throughput.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] If differentiated or guaranteed quality of service is offered, as opposed to best-effort communication, weighted fair queuing may be utilized.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In advanced packet radio wireless networks such as HSDPA (High-Speed Downlink Packet Access) 3.5G cellular system, **channel-dependent scheduling** may be used to take advantage of channel state information.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] If the channel conditions are favourable, the throughput and system spectral efficiency may be increased.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In even more advanced systems such as LTE, the scheduling is combined by channel-dependent packet-by-packet dynamic channel allocation, or by assigning OFDMA multi-carriers or other frequency-domain equalization components to the users that best can utilize them.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Earliest deadline first (EDF) or *least time to go* is a dynamic scheduling algorithm used in real-time operating systems to place processes in a priority queue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Whenever a scheduling event occurs (a task finishes, a new task is released, etc.), the queue will be searched for the process closest to its deadline, which will be the next to be scheduled for execution.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] With this strategy the scheduler arranges processes with the least estimated processing time remaining to be next in the queue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] This requires advanced knowledge or estimations about the time required for a process to complete.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The operating system assigns a fixed-priority rank to every process, and the scheduler arranges the processes in the ready queue in order of their priority.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Lower-priority processes get interrupted by incoming higher-priority processes.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The scheduler assigns a fixed time unit per process, and cycles through them.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] If the process completes within that time slice, it gets terminated otherwise, it is rescheduled after giving a chance to all other processes.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] This is used for situations in which processes are easily divided into different groups.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] For example, a common division is made between foreground (interactive) processes and background (batch) processes.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] These two types of processes have different response-time requirements and so may have different scheduling needs.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] It is very useful for shared memory problems.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] A work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that always tries to keep the scheduled resources busy if there are submitted jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In contrast, a non-work-conserving scheduler is a scheduler that, in some cases, may leave the scheduled resources idle despite the presence of jobs ready to be scheduled.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] A very common method in embedded systems is to schedule jobs manually.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] This can, for example, be done in a time-multiplexed fashion.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Sometimes the kernel is divided in three or more parts: Manual scheduling, preemptive and interrupt level.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Exact methods for scheduling jobs are often proprietary.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] When designing an operating system, a programmer must consider which scheduling algorithm will perform best for the use the system is going to see.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] There is no universal *best* scheduling algorithm, and many operating systems use extended or combinations of the scheduling algorithms above.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] For example, Windows NT/XP/Vista uses a multilevel feedback queue, a combination of fixed-priority preemptive scheduling, round-robin, and first-in, first-out algorithms.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In this system, threads can dynamically increase or decrease in priority depending on if it has been serviced already or if it has been waiting extensively.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Every priority level is represented by its own queue, with round-robin scheduling among the high-priority threads and FIFO among the lower-priority ones.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In this sense, response time is short for most threads, and short but critical system threads get completed very quickly.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Since threads can only use one time unit of the round-robin in the highest-priority queue, starvation can be a problem for longer high-priority threads.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The algorithm used may be as simple as round-robin in which each process is given equal time (for instance, 1 ms, usually between 1 ms and 100 ms) in a cycling list.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] So, process A executes for 1 ms, then process B, then process C, then back to process A.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] More advanced algorithms take into account process priority, or the importance of the process.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] This allows some processes to use more time than others.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The kernel always uses whatever resources it needs to ensure proper functioning of the system, and so can be said to have infinite priority.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In SMP systems, processor affinity is considered to increase overall system performance, even if it may cause a process itself to run more slowly.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] This generally improves performance by reducing cache thrashing.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] IBM OS/360 was available with three different schedulers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Later virtual storage versions of MVS added a *Workload Manager* feature to the scheduler, which schedules processor resources according to an elaborate scheme defined by the installation.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Very early MS-DOS and Microsoft Windows systems were non-multitasking, and as such did not feature a scheduler.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Windows 3.1x used a non-preemptive scheduler, meaning that it did not interrupt programs.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] It relied on the program to end or tell the OS that it didn't need the processor so that it could move on to another process.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] This is usually called cooperative multitasking.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Windows 95 introduced a rudimentary preemptive scheduler; however, for legacy support opted to let 16-bit applications run without preemption.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Windows NT-based operating systems use a multilevel feedback queue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] 32 priority levels are defined, 0 through 31, with priorities 0 through 15 being *normal* priorities and priorities 16 through 31 being soft real-time priorities, requiring privileges to assign.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] User interfaces and APIs work with priority classes for the process and the threads in the process, which are then combined by the system into the absolute priority level.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The scheduler was modified in Windows Vista to use the cycle counter register of modern processors to keep track of exactly how many CPU cycles a thread has executed, rather than just using an interval-timer interrupt routine.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Vista also uses a priority scheduler for the I/O queue so that disk defragmenters and other such programs do not interfere with foreground operations.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Mac OS 9 uses cooperative scheduling for threads, where one process controls multiple cooperative threads, and also provides preemptive scheduling for multiprocessing tasks.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The kernel schedules multiprocessing tasks using a preemptive scheduling algorithm.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] All Process Manager processes run within a special multiprocessing task, called the *blue task*.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Those processes are scheduled cooperatively, using a round-robin scheduling algorithm; a process yields control of the processor to another process by explicitly calling a blocking function such as `WaitNextEvent`.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Each process has its own copy of the Thread Manager that schedules that process's threads cooperatively; a thread yields control of the processor to another thread by calling `YieldToAnyThread` or `YieldToThread`.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] macOS uses a multilevel feedback queue, with four priority bands for threads – normal, system high priority, kernel mode only, and real-time.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Threads are scheduled preemptively; macOS also supports cooperatively scheduled threads in its implementation of the Thread Manager in Carbon.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Threads are primarily of interest for applications that currently consist of several asynchronous processes.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] These applications might impose a lighter load on the system if converted to a multithreaded structure.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] AIX 5 implements the following scheduling policies: FIFO, round robin, and fair round robin.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The FIFO policy has three different implementations: FIFO, FIFO2, and FIFO3.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The round robin policy is named SCHED_RR in AIX, and the fair round robin is called SCHED_OTHER.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Linux 1.2 used a round-robin scheduling policy.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Linux 2.2 added scheduling classes and support for symmetric multiprocessing (SMP).
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In Linux 2.4, an O(n) scheduler with a multilevel feedback queue with priority levels ranging from 0 to 140 was used; 0–99 are reserved for real-time tasks and 100–140 are considered nice task levels.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] For real-time tasks, the time quantum for switching processes was approximately 200 ms, and for nice tasks approximately 10 ms.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The scheduler ran through the run queue of all ready processes, letting the highest priority processes go first and run through their time slices, after which they will be placed in an expired queue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] When the active queue is empty, the expired queue will become the active queue and vice versa.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] However, some enterprise Linux distributions such as SUSE Linux Enterprise Server replaced this scheduler with a backport of the O(1) scheduler (which was maintained by Alan Cox in his Linux 2.4-ac Kernel series) to the Linux 2.4 kernel used by the distribution.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In versions 2.6.0 to 2.6.22, the kernel used an O(1) scheduler developed by Ingo Molnar and many other kernel developers during the Linux 2.5 development.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] For many kernels in this time frame, Con Kolivas developed patch sets which improved interactivity with this scheduler or even replaced it with his own schedulers.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Con Kolivas' work, most significantly his implementation of fair scheduling named Rotating Staircase Deadline (RSDL), inspired Ingo Molnár to develop the Completely Fair Scheduler (CFS) as a replacement for the earlier O(1) scheduler, crediting Kolivas in his announcement.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] CFS is the first implementation of a fair queuing process scheduler widely used in a general-purpose operating system.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The CFS uses a well-studied, classic scheduling algorithm called fair queuing originally invented for packet networks.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Fair queuing had been previously applied to CPU scheduling under the name stride scheduling.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The fair queuing CFS scheduler has a scheduling complexity of $O(\log N)$ , where N is the number of tasks in the runqueue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Choosing a task can be done in constant time, but reinserting a task after it has run requires $O(\log N)$ operations, because the run queue is implemented as a red–black tree.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The Brain Fuck Scheduler, also created by Con Kolivas, is an alternative to the CFS.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] In 2023, Peter Zijlstra proposed replacing CFS with an earliest eligible virtual deadline first scheduling (EEVDF) process scheduler.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The aim was to remove the need for CFS *latency nice* patches.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Linux 6.12 added support for scheduler extensions that can be added from userspace; this mechanism is known as sched_ext.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] An eBPF program can be loaded into the kernel to implement a scheduling policy.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] These schedulers can replace the default scheduler.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] FreeBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–255.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for interrupts, 64–127 for the top half of the kernel, 128–159 for real-time user threads, 160–223 for time-shared user threads, and 224–255 for idle user threads.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Also, like Linux, it uses the active queue setup, but it also has an idle queue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] NetBSD uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging from 0–223.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] 0–63 are reserved for time-shared threads (default, SCHED_OTHER policy), 64–95 for user threads that entered kernel space, 96–128 for kernel threads, 128–191 for user real-time threads (SCHED_FIFO and SCHED_RR policies), and 192–223 for software interrupts.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Solaris uses a multilevel feedback queue with priorities ranging between 0 and 169.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Priorities 0–59 are reserved for time-shared threads, 60–99 for system threads, 100–159 for real-time threads, and 160–169 for low priority interrupts.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Unlike Linux, when a process is done using its time quantum, it is given a new priority and put back in the queue.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] Solaris 9 introduced two new scheduling classes, namely fixed-priority class and fair share class.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The threads with fixed priority have the same priority range as that of the time-sharing class, but their priorities are not dynamically adjusted.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] The fair scheduling class uses CPU *shares* to prioritize threads for scheduling decisions.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] CPU shares indicate the entitlement to CPU resources.
[src:hashicorp-nomad/scheduling-computing] They are allocated to a set of processes, which are collectively known as a project.
